Data Preparation

Load Data

Load the data imported, processed and saved from data wrangle change score centroid and map data.R.

load("processed_data v2.RData")

Prepare Data

Keep distinct records within each time point only because keeping all pairwise records will inflate the number of observations in time 1 and 2.

data_long <- distinct(merged_data_record_all_long, tribe, time, FIPS, .keep_all = TRUE)

Create data.frame to include only tribes with time 1 and 2 data.

data_t1and2_long <- filter(data_long, tribe %in% tribes_time1and2_lst$tribe)

Check Data

First, confirm the data is correct, each tribe should have 2 summarized records in total, one for time 1 and one for time 2, so the resulted data.frame should has 0 row.

t1and2_lst <- group_by(data_t1and2_long, tribe, time) %>% 
  count() %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(tribe) %>%
  count() %>%
  filter(n < 2)

nrow(t1and2_lst)
## [1] 0

Test for Significant Difference

(1) Test for significant difference at the aggregate level

  • Welchs t-test (t.test, paired = FALSE) is a parameteric test for two-sample mean comparisions that does not assume equal variance.
  • Use Welchs t-test because the outcome precipitation is a continous measures.
  • Welchs t-test for dependent sample is not used because these are not true paired data, since we dont know which time 1 locations migrate to which time 2 locations and simply assume all possible migration routes happened.

Use all records

t.test(precip ~ time, data = data_long, paired = FALSE)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  precip by time
## t = 0.2028, df = 739.14, p-value = 0.8393
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -39.98078  49.19255
## sample estimates:
## mean in group time 1 mean in group time 2 
##             912.7505             908.1447
mean_t1 <- round(mean(filter(data_long, time == "time 1")$precip, na.rm = T), 2)
mean_t2 <- round(mean(filter(data_long, time == "time 2")$precip, na.rm = T), 2)
sd_t1 <- round(sd(filter(data_long, time == "time 1")$precip, na.rm = T), 2)
sd_t2 <- round(sd(filter(data_long, time == "time 2")$precip, na.rm = T), 2)
pvalue <- round(tidy(t.test(precip ~ time, data = data_long, paired = FALSE))$p.value, 3)
tvalue <- round(tidy(t.test(precip ~ time, data = data_long, paired = FALSE))$statistic, 3)
degreef <- round(tidy(t.test(precip ~ time, data = data_long, paired = FALSE))$parameter, 3)

Interpretation

  • At the aggregate level, the difference in precipitation between time 1 (M = 912.75, SD = 400.4) and time 2 (M = 908.14, SD = 588.1) was not statistically signficant (t(739.137)= 0.203, p = 0.839).

Use only records where tribes have time 1 and 2 data

t.test(precip ~ time, data = data_t1and2_long, paired = FALSE)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  precip by time
## t = 0.59691, df = 694.66, p-value = 0.5508
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -32.09259  60.13037
## sample estimates:
## mean in group time 1 mean in group time 2 
##             899.9031             885.8842
mean_t1 <- round(mean(filter(data_t1and2_long, time == "time 1")$precip, na.rm = T), 2)
mean_t2 <- round(mean(filter(data_t1and2_long, time == "time 2")$precip, na.rm = T), 2)
sd_t1 <- round(sd(filter(data_t1and2_long, time == "time 1")$precip, na.rm = T), 2)
sd_t2 <- round(sd(filter(data_t1and2_long, time == "time 2")$precip, na.rm = T), 2)
pvalue <- round(tidy(t.test(precip ~ time, data = data_t1and2_long, paired = FALSE))$p.value, 3)

Interpretation

  • At the aggregate level for tribes with migration, the difference in precipitation between time 1 (M = 899.9 SD = 411.62) and time 2 (M = 885.88, SD = 581.85) was also not statistically signficant (t(694.659)= 0.597, p = 0.551).

(2) Test for significant difference at tribe level

no_test <- group_by(data_t1and2_long, tribe) %>%
do(tryCatch( {tidy(t.test(precip ~ time, data = ., paired = FALSE))},
  error = function(e) {tidy(t.test(precip ~ time, data = data_t1and2_long)) %>% mutate(estimate = NA)}
    ))

no_test[!!rowSums(is.na(no_test)),-1] <- NA

no_test <- no_test %>%
  filter(!is.na(p.value)) %>% 
  nrow()

This can only be tested with the 184 tribes where migrations occured. Furthermore, only tribes where precipitation have changed between time points and with more than one data point at each time point can their differences be tested for statistical significance. This reduce the number of tribes from 184 to 110.

Run Welchs t-test in Batch

  • Run Welchs t-test in batch using group_by and do at the tribe level.
  • Include a try call to catch error.
  • Use tidy from broom package to format the results into a data.frame.
  • Replace NA estimate with all NA for that comparison.
model <- group_by(data_t1and2_long, tribe) %>%
do(tryCatch( {tidy(t.test(precip ~ time, data = ., paired = FALSE))},
  error = function(e) {tidy(t.test(precip ~ time, data = data_t1and2_long)) %>% mutate(estimate = NA)}
    ))

model[!!rowSums(is.na(model)),-1] <- NA

Calculate number of test based only on tribes where there is non-zero difference and sufficient data point in precipitation between time 1 and 2.

no_test <- nrow(filter(model, !is.na(p.value)))
  • Create sig column to flag statistical significance results.
  • p-value cutoff is adjusted to control for Type I error due to multiple comparisons using Bonferroni correction (p value threshold = .05 / number of tests or 110), adjusted p-value threshold = 0.0045455.
model <- model %>%
  mutate(sig = ifelse(p.value < .05 / no_test, "yes", "no"))
  • Add average precipitation, distance, and no of unique FIPS to help with interpretation
  • Rename some variables for prettier column headers
results_df <- inner_join(model, merged_data_tribe, by = "tribe") %>%
  mutate(`Avg Diff Precipitation` = avg_precip_t2 - avg_precip_t1) %>%
  select(tribe, sig, p.value, `Avg Diff Precipitation`, avg_precip_t1, avg_precip_t2, n_unique_FIPS_t1, n_unique_FIPS_t2, mid_dist) %>%
  arrange(p.value) %>%
  rename(
    `Avg Precipitation T1` = avg_precip_t1,
    `Avg Precipitation T2` = avg_precip_t2,
    `Unique FIPS T1` = n_unique_FIPS_t1,
    `Unique FIPS T2` = n_unique_FIPS_t2,
    `Mid Distance` = mid_dist)

Results Table

Ordered by p value in ascending order

datatable(results_df,
          filter = "top",
          options = list(pageLength = 20)) %>%
   formatRound(columns = c('p.value'), digits = 3) %>%
   formatRound(columns = c('Avg Diff Precipitation', 'Avg Precipitation T1', 'Avg Precipitation T2', 'Mid Distance'), digits = 2)
b_sig_tribe_lst <- filter(results_df, sig == "yes") %>%
  select(tribe)
sig_tribe_lst <- filter(results_df, p.value < .05) %>%
  select(tribe)

Interpretation

  • The mean precipitation comparisons for eight tribes (Chippewa, Chickasaw, Sioux, Caddo, Comanche, Kiowa, Sisseton, Cayuga, Lenape, Arapaho, Cheyenne, Creek, Chinook, Shoshone, Cowlitz, Arikara, Cherokee, Potawatomi, Iowa, Pawnee, Hidatsa, Mandan, Gros Ventre) achieve statistical significance when the Bonferroni correction is used.
  • The tests have low statistical power to detect differences given the number of observations at time 2 is much smaller than time 1.
  • If Bonferroni correction is not used, precipitation was significantly differ between time 1 and 2 for 23 tribes :(Chippewa, Chickasaw, Sioux, Caddo, Comanche, Kiowa, Sisseton, Cayuga, Lenape, Arapaho, Cheyenne, Creek, Chinook, Shoshone, Cowlitz, Arikara, Cherokee, Potawatomi, Iowa, Pawnee, Hidatsa, Mandan, Gros Ventre).
  • Results with NA p values are from tribes where there isnt sufficient data points in both time point to perform the planned statistical tests (Welchs t-test).

Overall Interpretation

  • Overall, no statistically significant difference was found at the aggregate level. At the tribe level, when correction for multiple comparisons was made, precipitations for eight tribes were found to be statistically differ between time 1 and time 2.

  • The lack of significant differences at the tribe level could be attributed to the low statistical power arises from the small number of observations at time 2. In some cases, there is only 1 data point in time 2 or time 1, which preclude the use of Welchs t-test to test for their mean differences.
